                        "id": "8418594f-2f82-4ed7-9b5e-978dd32acb57",
                        "exerciseName": "Nape stretching",
                        "exerciseDescription": "<p><strong>Complex of neck exercises. 2. Nape</strong></p><p>Exercise on the back of your neck.</p><p>Essential basic technique for a healthy neck!&nbsp;</p><p>- The neck gets longer and stronger;</p><p>- Mobility of the head increases;</p><p>- Tension is released;</p><p>- The back part of the neck is stretched and more flexible;</p><p>- Indispensable preparation for all the next exercises.</p><p><strong>Caution:&nbsp;</strong>As with all neck exercises, perform it very slowly and gently! If you do it correctly, you will feel comfortable at any time while exercising.</p><p>In this business, it is better to do it softly rather than zealously.</p><p>Breathe smoothly during any exercise. It is crucial for the result.</p><p>The word &ldquo;compensation&rdquo; here means a slight pressure against the main movement.</p><p><strong>Technique</strong></p><p><strong>1 Action</strong>. Head back on hump</p><p>- Stand in the upright position with the crown pointed upward.</p><p>- Lock your hands together behind your lower back. Lift the locked hands upward as high as you can while keeping your arms straight. Your trapezoid muscles would shape up to a hump.</p><p>- Use the hump as a base for your head, slowly let your head drop on the hump.</p><p>- Stay in this position for 4 inhale-exhale rounds.&nbsp;</p><p>- After exhaling for the 4th time, slowly start moving your head upwards while inhaling.&nbsp;</p><p>- Fix your head in the upright position for a couple of seconds and move on to stretching.</p><p><strong>2 Action</strong>. Stretching</p><p>- Lift your hands, lock them together with your fingers and place them on the back of your head.</p><p>-You&rsquo;ll feel the weight of your arms slightly pushing your head down. Allow it to do so, but DO NOT push it down with strength. Just the weight of your arms is enough to do the trick.</p><p>- Tilt your head down, feel the tension in the back of the neck, relax your arms.</p><p>- Stay in this position for the next 4 inhale-exhale rounds.&nbsp;</p><p>- Control your breathing. Breathe evenly in and out, do not hold the breath.</p><p><strong>3 Action</strong>. Compensation</p><p>- After the last exhaling, while inhaling you slowly start moving your head upwards with your locked hands compensating for this movement with slight resistance.&nbsp;</p><p>- Fix your head in a perfectly upright position. The head is slightly pushing against your locked hands.</p><p>- Stay in this position for 2 inhale-exhale rounds. Breathe deep and evenly.</p><p><strong>Repeat</strong> the actions 2 and 3 for 2 inhale-exhale rounds each.</p><p>- Close your eyes for a few seconds and feel your neck and its new position.</p><p><br></p><p><strong>Attention!</strong></p><p>No pressure on the head, while it is tilted toward the chest. Just the weight of your arms should perform the natural pressure. If you think, your hands might be too heavy, you should be especially careful and try to compensate for the natural pressure in order to make it lighter.</p><p>This exercise is good on its own, but you should never skip it out when doing the neck complex.</p><p><br></p><p><em>Take it easy!&nbsp;</em><span class=\"fr-emoticon fr-deletable fr-emoticon-img\" style=\"background: url(https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/emojione/2.0.1/assets/svg/1f60c.svg);\">&nbsp;</span>&nbsp;</p><p data-f-id=\"pbf\" style=\"text-align: center; font-size: 14px; margin-top: 30px; opacity: 0.65; font-family: sans-serif;\">Powered by <a href=\"https://www.froala.com/wysiwyg-editor?pb=1\" title=\"Froala Editor\">Froala Editor</a></p>",
