                        "id": "2945fa2a-b859-4fe0-8d30-c1deddd6fcb1",
                        "exerciseName": "Double chin massage",
                        "exerciseDescription": "<p><strong>Double chin massage</strong></p><p>Benefits:<br>- Double chin is reduced.<br>- Jawline is toned and fit.<br>- Lymph circulation is improved.<br>- A great non-invasive treatment for lymphedema* and tissue fibrosis** in the neck.</p><p>Face tissue swelling is one of the main problems concerning the face shape, in general. Normally we do not waste any thoughts on it. We just accept the fact that the face is swelling as years pass. In fact, the main reason for this is a clogged lymphatic system which makes our skin look thicker. We normally put up with it until it gets too heavy and starts pulling parts of a face down, bringing such unpleasant effects like loose skin, puffy lower eyelid and nasolabial folds.<br>Most of the lymph fluid from the face region goes through the lymph nodes in the neck area. If&nbsp;the lymph transport system doesn&rsquo;t work properly, it results in a clogged lymphatic system in the neck area. The more lymph is stagnating there, the more symptoms like uneven jawline, double chin, neck lines, fibrosis and lymphedema.<br>We are not going to dwell on the reasons for lymphedema, they are very complex and there are too many of them. Our goal is to make the lymph transport system work better in order to get rid of the unhealthy volume.</p><p><strong>Technique</strong><br><strong>1. Action</strong>. Warm-up with large pinches<br>All in all about 1 minute.<br>- You need both hands for this exercise. Use your thumbs and the index fingers formed to hooks. Pinch the area below the jaw. Try to grab as much soft tissues as possible when you do the pinches.<br>- Work your way through the area of your neck from the chin to Adam&#39;s apple. You can even go further down under the Adam&#39;s apple, if you feel like doing it.<br><strong>2. Action</strong>. Squeeze out excess of fluids<br>All in all about 1 minute for the both sides.<br>- Use the same thumbs and &ldquo;hooks&rdquo; but this time you work single-handed. On the right side you work with your right hand, on the left side with your left hand.<br>- Start working from the middle of the area under your chin. Take the thumb from the &ldquo;hook&rdquo; apart as much as possible. Place the thumb under the jaw angle, the &ldquo;hook&rdquo; should be under the chin. The thumb is for fixing and the &ldquo;hook&rdquo; is our working finger here. Squeeze out the soft tissues towards the thumb letting the flesh slip out from the pinch.<br>- As soon as the &ldquo;hook&rdquo; reaches the thumb, place the thumb closer to the ear and repeat the squeezing action. You may need to do up to 3 steps before you reach the ear.<br>- After that, place both the thumb and the &ldquo;hook&rdquo; further down along your neck and repeat the squeezing technique. Work your way through the whole area you warmed up in action 1.</p><p>Repeat the 2nd action on the other side.</p><p><strong>Attention!</strong><br>As always in this business, it is better to do it gently rather than zealously.<br>Especially when you do it for the first time. Later, you will figure out the correct amount of power you can apply.</p><p><em>Have fun! <span class=\"fr-emoticon fr-deletable fr-emoticon-img\" style=\"background: url(https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/emojione/2.0.1/assets/svg/1f609.svg);\">&nbsp;</span>&nbsp;</em></p><p>*Lymphedema is chronic tissue swelling that happens when the lymphatic transport capacity is exceeded.<br>**Tissue fibrosis is the phenomenon in which a tissue has a progressive deposition of collagen fibers with age. Tissue fibrosis is associated with aging of most of our organs, and it is the main pathology in arteriosclerosis, chronic bronchitis/emphysema, and benign prostatic hyperplasia. The causes and characteristics of fibrosis are analyzed with misrepair mechanism, a mechanism proposed in misrepair-accumulation aging theory.</p><p data-f-id=\"pbf\" style=\"text-align: center; font-size: 14px; margin-top: 30px; opacity: 0.65; font-family: sans-serif;\">Powered by <a href=\"https://www.froala.com/wysiwyg-editor?pb=1\" title=\"Froala Editor\">Froala Editor</a></p>",
