                        "id": "eb57e548-f522-4f0b-9ca0-6e4671cd646e",
                        "exerciseName": "Cheek-eyelid junction care",
                        "exerciseDescription": "<p><strong>Frictions at the eyelid-cheek junction</strong></p><p>The orbital muscle of the eye, like other active facial muscles, tends to accumulate residual spasm and shorten with age. It literally shrinks to the center and falls under the eyeball. The tissues around the eyes become thinner, and the subcutaneous fat is gradually replaced by tough collagen fibers.<br>Visually, the eyes seem to fall inward, and on the border of the eyelid and cheek a distinct ridge is formed, which makes the eyes seem even older. With this technique, we will work out the tissues on the eyelid-cheek border, get rid of fibrosis and return the tissues to their former youthful volume!</p><p><strong>Attention!</strong><br>The soft tissues in the orbital area are thin and delicate, they can react very differently to intense work. Pay attention to whether it became worse after the massages. If you suddenly find that there are more wrinkles under the eyes, or the eyes seem to have sunk even deeper, skip intensive work with the orbital area. It means that you do not get in grip the <strong>orbicularis oculi&nbsp;</strong>muscle and rub only skin. For now, &nbsp;spiral massage, lymph drainage and light kneading will be enough for you. You will be able to return to advanced eye area techniques when you restore good blood and lymph flow, and with it restore the metabolism process and tone of the skin.</p><p><strong>Technique:</strong><br>Place the index finger of one hand next to the inner corner of the eye on the border of the lower eyelid and cheek, and the other index finger next to the first at a distance of about half inch. Put them together so that a fold of underlying tissues is formed . Very carefully and gently start doing friction movements. Make about 10 light frictions at one place, and then reposition your fingers towards the middle of the eye. Repeat and again move your working fingers closer to the outer corner of the eye.<br>Try to work precisely with the tissues on the border of the eyelid and cheek, feel the very place where the thin skin of the eyelid turns into dense soft tissue. Grab the tissues deeper to catch the <strong>orbicularis oculi&nbsp;</strong>muscle into the grip. Depending on the state of your tissues, it can feel like an almost smooth transition or like a hard line falling inward.<br>If the fold of the soft tissues slips out of your fingers, don&#39;t worry, just grab it again, try to feel <strong>orbicularis oculi&nbsp;</strong>muscle and do the necessary amount of frictions.<br>Do not forget about the area in the outer corner of the eye, where your smile wrinkles start - crow&#39;s feet. There, the thin skin of the eyelids turns into the skin at the temples, and the orbital muscle of the eye intersects with the temporal muscle.</p><p><strong>2nd variation.</strong></p><p>You can do this technique with one hand. It will be even stronger. The main move here will the pinch. Try to get deeper between the eyeball and bone.</p><p>Avoid severe redness, do not squeeze too hard in an attempt to get rid of all the wrinkles at once. In this case, regularity is more important than intensity.<br>Even if you do not yet have obvious wrinkles and drooping of the lower eyelid, do not skip this technique. Wrinkles do not appear instantly, it takes years! The sooner you take care of the quality of the soft tissues in the orbital area, the longer you will not see wrinkles around your eyes.</p><p>Do it with pleasure and self-care! <span class=\"fr-emoticon fr-deletable fr-emoticon-img\" style=\"background: url(https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/emojione/2.0.1/assets/svg/1f60a.svg);\">&nbsp;</span>&nbsp;</p><p data-f-id=\"pbf\" style=\"text-align: center; font-size: 14px; margin-top: 30px; opacity: 0.65; font-family: sans-serif;\">Powered by <a href=\"https://www.froala.com/wysiwyg-editor?pb=1\" title=\"Froala Editor\">Froala Editor</a></p>",
