                        "id": "8737da18-ec88-4d19-912b-b66444992ffe",
                        "exerciseName": "Midcheek furrow correction",
                        "exerciseDescription": "<p><strong>Correction of the tear trough, nasojugal grove and midcheek furrow.</strong></p><p>Noticeable groove visually starting with tear trough, continuing with nosajugal crease and ending with midcheek furrow makes the face look very old! It is formed as a result of spasm and shortening of two muscle groups: F levators on one side and chewing muscles on the other. A groove lies between these two bundles of muscles, the tissues under it fibrosis and degrade. In the place of the crease, the skin becomes thinner. Our task is to disperse the tissues in the area of the this groove well, restore the volume of subcutaneous adipose tissue under it, and also shift the tissues &nbsp;up to where they were in their youth.</p><p><strong>Technique:</strong><br><strong>1 step</strong>. Tear trough rubbing.<br>First we fix the tissues of the lower eyelid so that the delicate skin under the eyes moves as little as possible and does not stretch. To do this, place the index finger on the lower orbit of the eye.</p><p>Next, we set two working fingers on the nasolabial fold next to the wing of the nose and move the entire tissue array upward, pressing the fold tightly against the fixing finger. With small-amplitude circling massaging movements, begin to thoroughly disperse the tissues, literally rubbing the fold between the fixing and working fingers. Circle motions are directed from center to periphery. &nbsp;20-30 seconds should be enough. If the fold slips out of the grip, collect it again.</p><p><strong>2 step</strong>. Nasojugal groove rubbing.<br>Now 2 fingers, index and middle, are fixing the lower eyelid.<br>Set the fingertips from the center of the orbit to the outer corner of the eye, the middle finger should rest just above the nasojugal crease. Working fingers start from the previous position, but the motion vector will be diagonal towards the 1st joint of the fixing middle finger.</p><p>It is important to work out exactly the array of soft tissues. On the contrary, to F2 frictions there is no need to push against the bone, but to rub the soft tissues between the fingers. At the end of the motion, the working fingers can dig under the middle fixing one, this is fine.</p><p>Also, 20-30 seconds should be enough to do this step.</p><p><strong>3 step</strong>. Midcheek furrow rubbing.<br>In the same manner, work on the area just below.<br>Fixing fingers stay in the previous position, and the working ones start from the corner of the mouth. Do the same circling massaging movements towards the 1st joint of the fixing finger for 20-30 seconds.</p><p><strong>4 step</strong>. Midcheek furrow rubbing with extension.<br>Replace the fixing fingers higher to the temple so that the fingertip of the middle finger would fix the outer corner of the eye. The working fingers start from the nasolabial fold next to the corner of the mouth. In the same manner, collect the fold and do the rubbing for 20-30 seconds.&nbsp;</p><p>Surely, massage the other side of your face with equal effort.</p><p><strong>Attention!</strong><br>Don&#39;t overdo it! Avoid severe redness of the skin and massage to bruises. It is necessary to work intensively, but carefully. Though, regularity is more important than intensity. If you think that after this massage the worked out area looks more sagging - let it relax for a day or 2 and definitely come back to it later. Recollect the baby power and half power rules for the next try.</p><p>Good luck! <span class=\"fr-emoticon fr-deletable fr-emoticon-img\" style=\"background: url(https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/emojione/2.0.1/assets/svg/1f917.svg);\">&nbsp;</span> <br>Alex</p><p data-f-id=\"pbf\" style=\"text-align: center; font-size: 14px; margin-top: 30px; opacity: 0.65; font-family: sans-serif;\"> <a href=\"https://www.froala.com/wysiwyg-editor?pb=1\" title=\"\"></a></p>",
