                        "id": "288d4e21-92b8-4fe9-bb54-10623414ef43",
                        "exerciseName": "Advanced temple lifting",
                        "exerciseDescription": "<p><strong>Advanced lifting of the temporal facia with muscle fibers separation</strong></p><p>Here we come to get to know what is fascia. üßê<br>Fascia is a band or sheet of connective tissue, primarily collagen, beneath the skin that attaches, stabilizes, encloses, and separates muscles and other internal organs.*<br>Temporal fascia surrounds temporal muscle. Due to its viscoelastic properties it can be stretched to accommodate needs of the organ. This stretching cannot happen as fast as muscle stretching. If left unattended, fascia increases its protective ability and looses elasticity, it can also build intercellular connections with neighbouring tissues. Even when we pull and stretch the muscle, the fascia gets stretched slowly. It takes quite a few regular stretching to return its elasticity and reposition to its origins. To separate temporal fascia from its neighbouring tissues we make small amplitude movements. And we do long pauses to remind the fascia its original state. With regular practice the muscles and its fasciae return to their righteous original position. To learn more about properties of fascia check out this free webinar from Tom Myers, this will set your mind in right direction. (<span style=\"color: rgb(44, 130, 201);\"><a href=\"https://www.anatomytrains.com/fascia-moves-webinar/\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\" target=\"_blank\"><u>link</u></a></span>)&nbsp;</p><p><br></p><p>This technique will help to straighten the temporal muscles, relieve residual spasm from them and make your eyes open wider.</p><p>You will not believe your eyes how much the eyebrows and upper eyelids can rise in response to this technique. At first, the effect will be temporary, but with regular exercise, the eyebrows and upper eyelids will rise, and the youthful look will remain with you!</p><p><strong>Important!</strong><br>In this technique, it is very important to work with the temporal muscles, and not just pull the skin up. Make sure that the palms are firmly fixed on the muscles, do not allow a strong feeling of tension on the skin of the eyelids.</p><p><strong>Technique:<br>1 step. Fibers separation.</strong><br>Place the fingers, of both hands, on the temples with the little fingers just above the outer tips of the eyebrows. Press the soft tissue with your fingers almost to the bone and hold the pressure at the beginning of the temporal muscle for 5-15 seconds. Keeping the pressure, with vibrating small-amplitude massage movements, move your fingers towards the crown of the head. Press your fingers tightly through the muscles to the skull bone. Movements must be confident and fast enough. Stop vibrating when the bases of the palms are resting on the temples.<br>Maintain pressure with your fingers, and place your palms firmly on the temporalis muscle.<br><strong>2 step. Lifting the temporalis.</strong><br>Without letting go of your pressed palms, rest your elbows on the table or knees and relax your head and neck. Allow your head to slide slowly under its weight, maintaining the appropriate palm pressure (you already know how to do this from the basic technique).<br><strong>3 step. Pause before finishing.</strong><br>The movement will end when the fingers meet at the crown of the head. Do not rush to release the tension of the tissues, the longer you hold them, the better the effect (more than 1 minute, however, can be excessive).</p><p>Return to the starting position and do the technique again, shifting the trajectory of the vibrating movements closer to the ears.</p><p>2 times should be enough, but if you really like, you can make a third one shifting the trajectory of vibrational movements behind the ears.</p><p><strong>Attention!</strong><br>You work with the big temporalis muscle and its fascia, not with the skin of the temples or eyes. Do not grip the tissues of your eyes with the bases of your palms to avoid excessive tension on the skin of the eyes!</p><p>See the world with your eyes wide open!üò≥üòÅ</p><p>*Marieb, Elaine Nicpon; Hoehn, Katja (2007). Human anatomy &amp; physiology. Pearson Education. p. 133. ISBN 978-0-321-37294-9.</p><p data-f-id=\"pbf\" style=\"text-align: center; font-size: 14px; margin-top: 30px; opacity: 0.65; font-family: sans-serif;\">Powered by <a href=\"https://www.froala.com/wysiwyg-editor?pb=1\" title=\"Froala Editor\">Froala Editor</a></p>",
