                        "id": "f70bc2f2-dbee-47ce-8c91-39e82b30c0b6",
                        "exerciseName": "Zygomatic area kneading",
                        "exerciseDescription": "<p><strong>Zygomatic area lifting. Kneading</strong></p><p>Kneading is an excellent technique in order to warm up the tissues well and prepare them for subsequent manual techniques, in addition, it has a lymphatic drainage effect and is effective against imperfections that form in the middle part of the face: nasolabial folds, notable eyelid-cheek border, helps to make the cheekbones more outlined. This technique is familiar to you from the basic course &quot;Look younger&quot;, in this variation it is a bit deeper.<br><span class=\"fr-video fr-deletable fr-fvc fr-dvb fr-draggable\" contenteditable=\"false\" draggable=\"true\"><iframe width=\"640\" height=\"360\" src=\"https://player.vimeo.com/video/543716230\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen=\"\" class=\"fr-draggable\"></iframe></span></p><p><strong>Technique:</strong><br><strong>1 step</strong>. Zygomatic kneading.<br>We put the bases of the palms parallel to the nose, we rest against the cheekbones so that you feel the muscles under the skin. Hold on 5-10 seconds, and then begin rolling movement on the tissues (2-3 times in one place), gradually rearranging the palms from the center to the periphery. Rolling movements are alike a wheel going over a bump, the soft tissues should not shift from their places.</p><p>We call this kind of rolling movements - kneading. Keep kneading from nose to ears.</p><p><strong>2 step</strong>. Orbital kneading.<br>Return the palms to the nose and rearrange them higher on the orbital area and rest for 5-10 seconds. With very light rolling movements gently do kneading along the border of the lower eyelid, 2-3 times. You may increase up to 5 if you enjoy it ;).<br>And then , do kneading along the arch of the eye socket under the eyebrow. Also 2-3 times. We do kneading always from center to periphery.</p><p>Be careful, do not press too hard on the eyes and try not to pull on the delicate skin of the eyelids.</p><p><strong>3 step</strong>. Cheeks kneading.<br>Rearrange the palms down to the corner of the lips. Press in to feel the teeth and rest for 5-10 seconds. 2-3 times of kneading in this place are enough for regular practice, increase to 5 if you got dense array of tissues there.</p><p><strong>4th step</strong>. Jawline kneading.<br>Move your palms even lower. And with the bases of your palms, work the tissues from the chin along the jaw to the ears. 2-5 times, according to your sensations..</p><p><strong>Important!</strong><br>When you do kneading, you need to work in depth, without shifting the tissue in any direction.<br><strong>Always do kneading from center to periphery.</strong></p><p>Good luck!<span class=\"fr-emoticon fr-deletable fr-emoticon-img\" style=\"background: url(https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/emojione/2.0.1/assets/svg/1f917.svg);\">&nbsp;</span><br>Alex</p><p data-f-id=\"pbf\" style=\"text-align: center; font-size: 14px; margin-top: 30px; opacity: 0.65; font-family: sans-serif;\">Powered by <a href=\"https://www.froala.com/wysiwyg-editor?pb=1\" title=\"Froala Editor\">Froala Editor</a></p>",
