                        "id": "0f61d87a-755f-4aad-ad59-2532c562e231",
                        "exerciseName": "Head rotations",
                        "exerciseDescription": "<p><strong>Head rotations</strong></p><p>This is an amazing exercise which is going to help you return mobility to your neck! It is a basic exercise that you need to have always at your disposal.&nbsp;</p><p>This exercise:</p><p>- improves your neck zone (cervical spine) functional mobility;</p><p>- warms up your neck muscles;</p><p>- dissolves possible congestion in the cervical zone;</p><p>- restores the physiological tone of the neck muscles back to normal;</p><p>- corrects the neck static;</p><p>- prevents osteochondrosis and arthritis in the neck area.</p><p><strong>Caution:&nbsp;</strong>You can practice it any time of the day in any convenient situation. Do it before you start with other neck exercises and also after it. But start by doing it very very gently.</p><p>If you are doing it for the first time in your life, you may be surprised by cracking sounds and possible sudden aches.&nbsp;</p><p><strong>The technique:</strong></p><ul><li>Don&rsquo;t forget to control your breathing while doing any exercise. Deep inhale and then long exhale without pauses.</li><li>Stand up straight, let your arms hang down relaxed, and reach upwards with the top of your head and relax.&nbsp;</li><li>Let&rsquo;s call it the crown of your head. It is also a nice to imagine that you have something very important on your head <span class=\"fr-emoticon fr-deletable fr-emoticon-img\" style=\"background: url(https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/emojione/2.0.1/assets/svg/1f607.svg);\">&nbsp;</span> .</li><li>Then slowly drop your head as if you would try to touch your chest with the chin while exhaling.&nbsp;</li><li>Start to move your crown to the left and upwards doing semicircle while inhaling until your head gets to the position when the back of it looks down and you look up.</li><li>Continue the rotation from this position while exhaling by pointing your crown to the right then drop your chin down again. Imagine the crown drawing circles over your head.&nbsp;</li><li>Continue rotations to the right and do it 4 more times. Do not speed up! Keep doing it gently even if you feel alright after the first circle.</li><li>Do the same rotations to the left side. 5 times.&nbsp;</li><li>Keep doing it slowly and gently.</li><li>The larger circles you can draw with your crown, the more flexible and prepared for further exercises your neck is.</li></ul><p><strong>Attention!&nbsp;</strong>The technique is simple but please pay much attention to what you feel while doing the exercise. Any sharp pain can be a signal to cervical spine osteochondrosis. In that case you have to be very careful and attentive to your neck area. Any other exercise for your neck should be done very gently.&nbsp;</p><p>Do not ask me to diagnose what can be wrong with your neck, I am not a doctor. Besides, in that case, you need to see a doctor in person to get the correct diagnosis.</p><p><strong>Tale:&nbsp;</strong>PLEASE DO NOT THINK THIS IT IS NOT YOUR CASE!&nbsp;</p><p>I made this mistake when I did this neck exercise for the first time at the age of 40, 8 years after my last yoga class. I thought I was still flexible enough and stretching my neck would be an easy task.</p><p>It WAS! &nbsp;Very easy... <span class=\"fr-emoticon fr-deletable fr-emoticon-img\" style=\"background: url(https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/emojione/2.0.1/assets/svg/1f62d.svg);\">&nbsp;</span>&nbsp; BUT I ended up with a lumbago in my neck area which kept me from doing any other neck exercises for the next half a year. I had to downgrade it and go through a rehabilitation course to return mobility, strength and healthy feeling in the neck. This course is now called &quot;Take it easy&quot;, it consists of 20 easy exercises aimed at returning the mobility to your spine, and you can find this amazing course in the app.&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Extra:&nbsp;</strong>Head rotations can be done in a sitting position, too. The standing position is more<em>&nbsp;</em>preferred just because all the following neck exercises are done from a standing position.</p><p><em>Good luck!</em> <span class=\"fr-emoticon fr-deletable fr-emoticon-img\" style=\"background: url(https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/emojione/2.0.1/assets/svg/1f609.svg);\">&nbsp;</span>&nbsp;</p><p><br></p><p><strong>Have you tried?</strong></p><p>I bet you have heard many interesting sounds by now! :)) &nbsp;Clicks, crunching and even cracks are kind of normal... They are even normally expected.</p><p>I have been doing this exercise every day for past 4 years. My neck still does some clicking and crunching from time to time, but a lot less than before and I am no longer having any concerns about getting a lumbago.&nbsp;</p><p><br></p><p>Got sudden pain? Do not hesitate to consult your doctor!</p><p data-f-id=\"pbf\" style=\"text-align: center; font-size: 14px; margin-top: 30px; opacity: 0.65; font-family: sans-serif;\">Powered by <a href=\"https://www.froala.com/wysiwyg-editor?pb=1\" title=\"Froala Editor\">Froala Editor</a></p>",
