                        "id": "fb50174e-97b7-49eb-9a6a-b8e86a7e9c38",
                        "exerciseName": "F1 relaxation",
                        "exerciseDescription": "<p><strong>F1 muscle relaxation (the levator muscle of the nose lifting the upper lip and the wing of the nose)&nbsp;</strong></p><p>You can relax the F1 muscle using the technique of the ischemic compression and stretch the muscle using the myofascial correction.&nbsp;</p><p>The benefits:</p><p><span class=\"fr-emoticon fr-deletable fr-emoticon-img\" style=\"background: url(https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/emojione/2.0.1/assets/svg/1f449.svg);\">&nbsp;</span>&nbsp; easing the tension in the muscle responsible for lifting the lip and the wing of the nose;<br><span class=\"fr-emoticon fr-deletable fr-emoticon-img\" style=\"background: url(https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/emojione/2.0.1/assets/svg/1f449.svg);\">&nbsp;</span>&nbsp; stretching the F1 muscle fascia;<br><span class=\"fr-emoticon fr-deletable fr-emoticon-img\" style=\"background: url(https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/emojione/2.0.1/assets/svg/1f449.svg);\">&nbsp;</span>&nbsp; unevenness around the nose decrease;<br><span class=\"fr-emoticon fr-deletable fr-emoticon-img\" style=\"background: url(https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/emojione/2.0.1/assets/svg/1f449.svg);\">&nbsp;</span>&nbsp; the nasolabial folds at the base of the nose are smoothed out</p><p><span class=\"fr-video fr-deletable fr-fvc fr-dvb fr-draggable\" contenteditable=\"false\" draggable=\"true\"><iframe width=\"640\" height=\"360\" src=\"https://player.vimeo.com/video/542199029\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen=\"\" class=\"fr-draggable\"></iframe></span><br></p><p><br></p><p><strong>Technique</strong></p><p><strong>1</strong> action.<strong>&nbsp;Warming up</strong><br>We use the F muscle massage learned in the basic course. Let&#39;s take a good look at F levators, especially at F1.</p><p><strong>2 action</strong>.<br>step 1. <strong>Compression</strong><br>With one index finger, we fix F1 at the level of the orbit, pressing the tissue tightly to the bone. With the second index finger, we press all soft tissue from the wing of the nose to the fixing one, forming a fold of tissues, while we think about the muscle and try to squeeze it. We hold the clamp for 20-30 seconds. (4 inhale-exhale rounds)</p><p>Step 2. <strong>Pressing</strong><br>We put both index fingers in the middle of F1 and sink them to the bone, hold the pressure for 5-10 seconds.</p><p>The task is to push the muscle in the middle, then stretching will follow.</p><p>In order not to be confused of the fact you could stretch the skin too much in step 3, you can push in, creating some additional skin fold for stretching beforehand.</p><p>Step 3. <strong>Stretching</strong><br>Without releasing the pressure, we stretch the F1 muscle towards its beginning and end very slowly. The upper finger slowly moves to the lacrimal canal, and the lower to the wing of the nose. Ideally, movement should last the same amount of time as compression. When the fingers have reached the end points, we continue to hold the pressure on them for another 5-10 seconds and release.</p><p>Step 4. <strong>Soothing the skin</strong><br>The top layers of the skin may look crumpled for a short time after such intense pressure and stretch marks. Let&#39;s help them find their rightful place as quickly as possible.</p><p>Using these light massage movements, you bring the skin back to the place where it is supposed to be. Pay attention to your sensations. After the first times you perform this massage, your muscle may ache a little, this is absolutely normal.&nbsp;</p><p><br></p><p>Good luck!<span class=\"fr-emoticon fr-deletable fr-emoticon-img\" style=\"background: url(https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/emojione/2.0.1/assets/svg/1f60c.svg);\">&nbsp;</span>&nbsp;</p><p data-f-id=\"pbf\" style=\"text-align: center; font-size: 14px; margin-top: 30px; opacity: 0.65; font-family: sans-serif;\">Powered by <a href=\"https://www.froala.com/wysiwyg-editor?pb=1\" title=\"Froala Editor\">Froala Editor</a></p>",
