                "id": "5bb45af6-f6d7-4a86-9870-8de018be761e",
                "exerciseName": "Neck sides",
                "exerciseDescription": "<p><strong>Complex of neck exercises. 3. Sides</strong></p><p>Basics, basics for every day!<br>Exercise on the sides of your neck.</p><p>- Your neck gets long and strong;</p><p>- The side muscles of your neck are relaxed and better supplied with blood;</p><p>- Tension in your shoulders is reduced;</p><p>- Your head&rsquo;s supply with blood also improves, which results in a relief of headaches and shoulder pain.</p><p><strong>Caution:&nbsp;</strong>If you do it correctly, you will feel comfortable at any time while exercising.<br>Slow and gentle movements are the key to a healthy neck in this exercise.<br>The word &ldquo;compensation&rdquo; here means a slight pressure against the main movement.</p><p><strong>Technique</strong></p><p><strong>1 Action</strong>. Hump</p><p>- Stand in the upright position, stretch your crown upwards, relax your shoulders and arms.</p><p>- Put your right hand on your waist so that your arm and a bodyside would make a triangle. Now stretch the long side of this triangle by lifting the right shoulder as high as possible. Your trapezoid muscle should make a hump.</p><p>- Use this hump as base for your neck and your head, tilt your head slowly toward the uplifted shoulder. Your neck must firmly meet with the hump that you created with your trapezoid muscle, the ear may not necessarily touch the shoulder - it is not what we are aiming for. The goal is to get a slight pressure of the contracted trapezoids on the right side of your neck.</p><p>- Control your breathing. Breathe smoothly. Try to make your breathing in and out equally long.&nbsp;</p><p>- Keep this position for 4 deep inhale-exhale rounds; Return your head to the upright position and let your strained arm relax, spot the difference in sensations to the opposite side.</p><p><strong>2 Action</strong>. Stretching</p><p>- Keep your head in the upright position. Put your left hand over the head as if you were trying to grab your right ear. Let your left palm rest on the right side of your head.</p><p>- Tilt your head slowly to the left &ndash; the opposite side of where you made a hump previously. The hump and the neck are getting stretched now.</p><p>- The hand rests on your head without any tension, keep it relaxed. The hand performs slight pressure using its own weight only. Do not push!</p><p>- Relax the shoulder of the arm that rests on your head.</p><p>- Control your breathing. Breathe smoothly. Try to inhale and exhale equally long.&nbsp;</p><p>- Keep this position for the next 4 deep inhale-exhale rounds.</p><p><strong>3. Action</strong>. Compensation</p><p>- Return the head slowly in the upright position. The hand now is compensating the return action of the head, keeping the neck in the stretched state. Let the palm be in the same place until the very end of the action.</p><p>When your head is straight up with your hand compensating it with a slight pressure, keep this compensating pressure for the next 2 rounds of breathing in and out. Both the head and the hand &laquo;want&raquo; to keep the head in the perfectly upright position.</p><p>Start slowly with the stretching action again. Stay in the stretched position for 2 inhale and exhale rounds. Return your head to the upright position with the compensating pressure by your hand.</p><p>Now let your hand down. Relax. Close your eyes for 5 seconds and spot the difference between the left and the right side.</p><p>Repeat the sequence for the other side of your body.&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Attention!</strong></p><p>As with all neck exercises, perform it very slowly&nbsp;and be attentive to your sensations. If you do it right and keep your neck as long as possible in every position, you are not going to experience any discomfort.</p><p>! DO NOT try to reach shoulders with your ears. This can cause serious troubles to your neck; it is not the action we need.&nbsp;</p><p><br></p><p>Tale:</p><p>Well, I do this exercise every day. At least once in the morning as a part of the neck complex. I also do it any other time of the day when I feel discomfort in the neck-shoulder area. It is a great relaxation technique!</p><p><br></p><p>Have you tried?</p><p>What were your sensations in the left and right side before you did the opposite side?</p><p><br></p><p><em>Take care of your neck!&nbsp;</em><br><em>It is the pedestal for your pretty face</em> <span class=\"fr-emoticon fr-deletable fr-emoticon-img\" style=\"background: url(https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/emojione/2.0.1/assets/svg/1f64f.svg);\">&nbsp;</span> <span class=\"fr-emoticon fr-deletable fr-emoticon-img\" style=\"background: url(https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/emojione/2.0.1/assets/svg/1f60c.svg);\">&nbsp;</span>&nbsp;</p><p data-f-id=\"pbf\" style=\"text-align: center; font-size: 14px; margin-top: 30px; opacity: 0.65; font-family: sans-serif;\">Powered by <a href=\"https://www.froala.com/wysiwyg-editor?pb=1\" title=\"Froala Editor\">Froala Editor</a></p>",
