                "id": "2b1d4343-6825-448d-82de-fe6d2ba2637b",
                "exerciseName": "Trapezius stretching",
                "exerciseDescription": "<p><strong>Neck complex of exercises. 4. Trapezius</strong><br>Stretching the trapezius muscles.</p><p>- Your head posture improves;</p><p>- The neck gets longer and stronger;</p><p>- Tension in shoulders is released;</p><p>- Your head&rsquo;s supply with blood also improves;</p><p>- The better feeling in the body as a whole. &nbsp;</p><p><strong>Caution:</strong> Please perform this exercise slowly and gently. Remember, be especially careful if you never trained your neck muscles, we don&rsquo;t want to risk a lumbago. If you do the technique correctly, the neck will only get stronger and longer.</p><p><strong>Technique</strong></p><p><strong>1. Action</strong>. Rest on the hump</p><p>- Stand up in the upright position with a hand on your waist, your thumb looking down and your middle finger pointing to the spine bone. Your palm is resting on the part of your body where you suppose your kidney. Move your elbow backwards. Your arm and the bodyside would make a triangle. Now stretch the long side of this triangle by lifting your shoulder as high as possible. Your trapezius muscles should make a hump. This hump will be the base for the back of your head. Now turn your head in the opposite direction to the hump and look upwards. The back of your head should comfortably rest on the hump. No extra tension here.<br>- Stay in this position for 4 inhale-exhale rounds. Breathe evenly.</p><p><strong>2. Action</strong>. Stretching</p><p>- Return your head to the upright position and let your strained arm relax.<br>- With the other hand, take the back of your head, so that your wrist lies on the top of the head and fingers are pointing down. Ideally, the elbow would look outstretched. The hand here controls the following stretching.<br>- Tilt your head towards the chest, then move it slowly to the armpit of your controlling arm. Stretch your chin towards the armpit. Stay in this position for 4 inhale-exhale rounds. Breathe evenly, feel the muscles being stretched, starting from your skull and ending in your shoulder.</p><p><strong>3. Action</strong>. Compensation</p><p>- Return your head to the upright position by going the same way back. The controlling hand compensates the movement, which has the effect of slowing down the return movement with its natural weight.<br>- Stay in the upright position for the next 2 inhale-exhale rounds. The controlling hand is fixing the head and doesn&rsquo;t let it go backwards. Yet the all-up tension would be pointed up.</p><p>Repeat the stretching and fixing sequence and hold it for 2 inhale-exhale rounds each.&nbsp;</p><p>Repeat the sequence for the other side of your body.</p><p>It is the last exercise of the neck complex. It is advisable to do the <strong>head rotations after</strong> it.</p><p><strong>Attention!</strong></p><p>The controlling hand is for control only. Do not push while stretching. Its own weight is just enough pressure. If you think your hand might be too heavy, do not let all of its weight lay on your head. Listen to your body and try to find the right pressure.</p><p>Do the neck complex of exercises every day, and soon you will be amazed at how much longer your neck would become.<span class=\"fr-emoticon fr-deletable fr-emoticon-img\" style=\"background: url(https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/emojione/2.0.1/assets/svg/1f642.svg);\">&nbsp;</span>&nbsp;</p><p><br></p><p><em>Take care! <span class=\"fr-emoticon fr-deletable fr-emoticon-img\" style=\"background: url(https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/emojione/2.0.1/assets/svg/1f60c.svg);\">&nbsp;</span>&nbsp;</em></p><p data-f-id=\"pbf\" style=\"text-align: center; font-size: 14px; margin-top: 30px; opacity: 0.65; font-family: sans-serif;\">Powered by <a href=\"https://www.froala.com/wysiwyg-editor?pb=1\" title=\"Froala Editor\">Froala Editor</a></p>",
