                "id": "1ea530e5-9132-4bd5-9856-e4e436a1b40c",
                "exerciseName": "F levator massage",
                "exerciseDescription": "<p><strong>Massage of the muscle that lifts both the upper lip and of the wing of the nose (F1) and the muscles that lift the upper lip (F2)</strong></p><p>The muscles you work out today not only lift the upper lip and nose wings but are also responsible for forming small bumps aside of the nose and nasolabial folds. Today you learn the first basic technique, so please pay special attention to these muscles.</p><p>At first, a little bit of the anatomy.<br><span class=\"fr-video fr-deletable fr-fvc fr-dvb fr-draggable fr-active\" contenteditable=\"false\" draggable=\"true\"><iframe width=\"640\" height=\"360\" src=\"https://player.vimeo.com/video/542173520\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen=\"\" class=\"fr-draggable\"></iframe></span><br>These muscles have long scientific names:<br>1. The muscle that lifts the upper lip and nose wing is called Musculus levator labii superioris alaequae nasi in Latin. It runs along the nose. Contracted it lifts the upper lip and the tip of the nose. The muscle is attached to the upper frontal process of the maxilla (visibly under the lacrimal canals of the eyes) &nbsp;and inserts into the skin of the lateral part of the nostril and upper lip.(F1)<br>2. The muscle that lifts the upper lip (lat. Musculus levator labii superioris) starts at the infraorbital margin (the lower margin of the eye socket) above the infraorbital foramen (a small opening in the bone below) and inserts into the skin of the lateral part of the nostril and upper lip. (F2)<br>These both muscles are very important for facial expressions. They contract visibly when we smell something stinky and say &quot;Phi ..&quot;. Therefore, as it is somewhat cumbersome to use their full names and for the sake of simplicity, we will call the one that is closer to the nose - F1, and the one that is farther from the nose - F2.<br>The F1 and F2 are the upper lip lifting muscles.<br>By contracting, they lift the lip and also form the nasolabial fold and the bumps above it. In a contracted state, the nasolabial fold is always present on the face ... and becomes more distinguished, if you do not relax these F lifters muscles properly.</p><p>So, let&#39;s start relaxing the F lifters muscles. At the same time, you get an excellent lymphatic drainage of the nasal area, which has lots of benefits:<br>- The nasolabial folds start to shrink.<br>- The asymmetry of the nose and the lacrimal grooves is leveled off.<br>- The bruises, dark circles and puffiness under the eyes starts to diminish.<br>- The F muscles are relaxed and prepared for the more advanced techniques.</p><p><strong>Caution:</strong> Remember the rule of a one-year-old child&rsquo;s strength. Do not hurt yourself. You should feel comfortable during the whole exercise. You can adjust the strength for this exercise yourself later.&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Technique</strong><br>- You need both index and middle fingers for this exercise. Place them on the nasolabial fold so that the middle fingers are in the corners of the nose wings. The index and middle fingers are pressed together.<br>- Press in the soft tissues slightly, hold it like this for 3 to 5 seconds, and then begin small-amplitude circular massage movements. Circular motions in this case are similar to digging: inward, to the nose, then upwards with pressure, then outwards releasing the pressure and finally down.<br>- After a few circular movements, the index finger will reach the orbital bone. As soon as you feel this, raise your index finger, you no longer need it for the massage. Continue massaging with your middle fingers only until they reach the lacrimal canAls of the eyes.<br>- Slide your middle fingers to the nose wings starting from the lacrimal canals. The fingers go straight down the The muscle that lifts the upper lip and nose wing (F1). Feel them stretching and relaxing.<br>- Repeat it one more time. 2 sets shouldn&rsquo;t take longer than a minute.<br>- When you are done with the exercise, smooth out the skin surface pressing it with your fingers and moving upwards from below. Try to &ldquo;place&rdquo; the skin the way you would like to have it. It shouldn&rsquo;t take more than 5 to10 seconds.</p><p><strong>Attention!</strong><br>The exercise is easy and comforting but don&rsquo;t get carried away too much the first time. Remember, in this business, regularity is more important than intensity. And the increased intensity in the early stages can lead to discomfort the next day, which may make you want to stop or take a break. And breaks during the study course are not really useful.</p><p><em>Good luck! <span class=\"fr-emoticon fr-deletable fr-emoticon-img\" style=\"background: url(https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/emojione/2.0.1/assets/svg/1f60c.svg);\">&nbsp;</span>&nbsp;</em></p><p data-f-id=\"pbf\" style=\"text-align: center; font-size: 14px; margin-top: 30px; opacity: 0.65; font-family: sans-serif;\">Powered by <a href=\"https://www.froala.com/wysiwyg-editor?pb=1\" title=\"Froala Editor\">Froala Editor</a></p>",
