                "id": "a65a9893-7468-47aa-931a-660de36c4763",
                "exerciseName": "Relaxation of masseters",
                "exerciseDescription": "<div><div><div><div><p><strong>Relaxation of the large chewing muscles.<br>(the superficial and deep masseter muscles)</strong></p><p>Almost all people have masseters muscles in residual spasm. We chew and smile many times a day, and when we&rsquo;re nervous or angry, we grit our teeth. With age, this residual spasm leads to shortening and thickening of the chewing muscles. When we are young, these muscles lie flat from the cheekbones to the lower jaw... Because of the spasm, the muscles gather in one dense bump, pull the corner of the lower jaw upward, disrupting the performance of the mandibular joint, change the angle of inclination of the lower jaw, and the tissues of the cheeks are sagging down and displacing to the center.<br>Relaxing the chewing muscles helps to:<br><span class=\"fr-emoticon fr-deletable fr-emoticon-img\" style=\"background: url(https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/emojione/2.0.1/assets/svg/1f449.svg);\">&nbsp;</span>&nbsp; restore a clear oval of the face.<br><span class=\"fr-emoticon fr-deletable fr-emoticon-img\" style=\"background: url(https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/emojione/2.0.1/assets/svg/1f449.svg);\">&nbsp;</span>&nbsp; reduce or completely get rid of defects in the middle part of the face, such as: nasolabial folds, flabby sagging cheeks.<br><span class=\"fr-emoticon fr-deletable fr-emoticon-img\" style=\"background: url(https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/emojione/2.0.1/assets/svg/1f449.svg);\">&nbsp;</span>&nbsp; get rid of the habit of clenching teeth, due to which teeth will wear out less, prevention of bruxism.</p><p><strong>Attention!</strong><br>Massaging the chewing muscles can be painful both during execution and for a while after. This is normal and will go away with continued practice. You can relieve discomfort with a dry warm compress on the area of the chewing muscles.</p><p><strong>Technique:</strong><br><strong>1 step</strong>. Warm up.<br>Start the massage by warming up the chewing muscles.<br>Perform it with the upper part of the palm (metacarpophalangeal joints, see picture below), with the pads at the base of the fingers. Open your mouth, relax the lower jaw and knead the large chewing muscles in circular movements from the center to the periphery for 30 seconds. You can also do warm up with fingertips as we did in basic course.</p><p><span class=\"fr-video fr-deletable fr-fvc fr-dvb fr-draggable\" contenteditable=\"false\" draggable=\"true\"><iframe width=\"640\" height=\"360\" src=\"https://player.vimeo.com/video/576367915\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen=\"\" class=\"fr-draggable\"></iframe></span><br></p><p><strong>2 step</strong>. Stretching the Superficial and Deep Masseter muscles.<br>The pads in the upper part of the palm (metacarpophalangeal joints) will be the working ones.<br>Put you palms on the cheeks so that proximal interphalangeal joints rest on the cheekbones. Pull soft tissues up to reach the cheeckbone with the working pads, press them in and relax the lower jaw slightly opening the mouth. Now slowly pull the pressed the Superficial and Deep Masseter muscles down in 5 seconds. Without letting the skin off return the working pads to the starting position. Repeat this sequence 3-5 times.</p><p><span class=\"fr-video fr-deletable fr-fvc fr-dvb fr-draggable\" contenteditable=\"false\" draggable=\"true\"><iframe width=\"640\" height=\"360\" src=\"https://player.vimeo.com/video/576369287\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen=\"\" class=\"fr-draggable\"></iframe></span></p><p>Proceed to Stretching pterigoids.</p></div></div></div></div><p data-f-id=\"pbf\" style=\"text-align: center; font-size: 14px; margin-top: 30px; opacity: 0.65; font-family: sans-serif;\">Powered by <a href=\"https://www.froala.com/wysiwyg-editor?pb=1\" title=\"Froala Editor\">Froala Editor</a></p>",
